> > Also, you cannot tell from a code snippet `repository.findOne(Queries.customersBySales(), …);` how many arguments the specification expects while a design such as `repository.findOne(Queries.customersBySales(tenant, salesThreshold));` clearly defines expectations and it comes with IDE support telling you which parameters you should specify.
> 
> How about introduce sub interface `ParameterizedSpecification`?
> 
> ```java
> 	interface ParameterizedSpecification<T> extends Specification<T> {
> 
> 		Map<String, Object> getParameters();
> 
> 	}
> ```
> 
> Then you can do like this:
> 
> ```java
> 	public static ParameterizedSpecification<User> userHasAgeLessThanParam(Integer age) {
> 
> 		return new ParameterizedSpecification<>() {
> 
> 			@Override
> 			public Predicate toPredicate(Root<User> root, CriteriaQuery<?> query, CriteriaBuilder cb) {
> 				return cb.lessThan(root.get("age").as(Integer.class), cb.parameter(Integer.class, "age"));
> 			}
> 
> 			@Override
> 			public Map<String, Object> getParameters() {
> 				return Map.of("age", age);
> 			}
> 
> 		};
> 
> 	}
> ```

